## üìÑ YAML File Descriptions

### 1Ô∏è‚É£ Pod (`pod.yaml`)
- Smallest deployable unit in Kubernetes
- Runs one or more containers
- Used mainly for testing and learning

---

### 2Ô∏è‚É£ Deployment (`deployment.yaml`)
- Manages multiple Pod replicas
- Supports rolling updates and rollbacks
- Commonly used for stateless applications

---

### 3Ô∏è‚É£ Service (`service.yaml`)
- Provides stable network access to Pods
- Types include:
  - ClusterIP
  - NodePort
  - LoadBalancer

---

### 4Ô∏è‚É£ ConfigMap (`configmap.yaml`)
- Stores configuration data (key-value pairs)
- Used for environment variables or config files
- Non-sensitive data only

---

### 5Ô∏è‚É£ Secret (`secrets.yaml`)
- Stores sensitive information
- Base64 encoded
- Used for passwords, API keys, tokens

---

### 6Ô∏è‚É£ Persistent Volume (`pv.yaml`)
- Represents physical storage
- Provisioned by administrator
- Independent of Pods lifecycle

---

### 7Ô∏è‚É£ Persistent Volume Claim (`pvc.yaml`)
- Requests storage from PV
- Used by Pods to attach storage

---

### 8Ô∏è‚É£ StatefulSet (`statefulset.yaml`)
- Used for stateful applications (databases)
- Provides stable network identity
- Maintains persistent storage

---

### 9Ô∏è‚É£ Job (`job.yaml`)
- Executes tasks once
- Ensures completion
- Example: database migration

---

### üîü CronJob (`cronjob.yaml`)
- Runs Jobs on a schedule
- Similar to Linux cron
- Example: backups, cleanup tasks

---

### 1Ô∏è‚É£1Ô∏è‚É£ Ingress (`ingress.yaml`)
- Manages external access to services
- Works with Ingress Controller (NGINX, ALB)
- Supports routing and TLS

